tatistics</a>, <a data-href=\"Data Science\" href=\"2-tags/data-science.html\" class=\"internal-link\" target=\"_self\" rel=\"noopener nofollow\">Data Science</a>, <a href=\".?query=tag:ritvikmath\" class=\"tag is-unresolved\" target=\"_self\" rel=\"noopener nofollow\" data-href=\"#ritvikmath\">#ritvikmath</a><br>\nThe notes are based on <a data-tooltip-position=\"top\" aria-label=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Z6HGJMUakmc&amp;list=PLvcbYUQ5t0UEkf2NUEo7XSsyVTyeEk3Gq&amp;index=9\" rel=\"noopener nofollow\" class=\"external-link is-unresolved\" href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Z6HGJMUakmc&amp;list=PLvcbYUQ5t0UEkf2NUEo7XSsyVTyeEk3Gq&amp;index=9\" target=\"_self\">this video</a>.Basic assumptions about the data in a regression setting:\nComment, I am not so familiar with the second assumption. This is certainly not an OLS assumption. Maximize the probability by choosing a .\nBecause is not related to , is the likelihood that we know in frequentist statistics. is the prior of the estimated coefficient.Notice that the pdf on the right of is , and .Using the most common prior <br>The will be explored and sampled by the <a data-tooltip-position=\"top\" aria-label=\"Hamilton Monte Carlo (HMC)\" data-href=\"Hamilton Monte Carlo (HMC)\" href=\"1-random-notes/hamilton-monte-carlo-(hmc).html\" class=\"internal-link\" target=\"_self\" rel=\"noopener nofollow\">HMC</a> MCMC algorithm.<br>Therefore, back to <a data-href=\"#^c1f828\" href=\"#^c1f828\" class=\"internal-link\" target=\"_self\" rel=\"noopener nofollow\">^c1f828</a>The signs are flipped, so it's ARGMIN now.\nWe get rid of the things that are unrelated to in and .Because is positive, it doesn't change when we multiply the things in with .At the end, replace the squared symbol with norm.\nDoesn't this look similar?\nWhen we re-write as , the way is estimated is the same as ridged regressions.Therefore, the variance of the prior distribution decides how much we punish overfitting.\nThe smaller the variance is, the larger the penalty term will play a role.\nWe can imagine that if we use a more certain prior, the evidence needed to sway the prior has to be even stronger than when we consider the prior to be uncertain (with a larger ).","aliases":[],"inlineTags":[],"frontmatterTags":[],"headers":[{"heading":"Convergence with the regularization concept","level":5,"id":"Convergence_with_the_regularization_concept_0"}],"links":["2-tags/statistics.html","2-tags/data-science.html","?query=tag:ritvikmath","1-random-notes/hamilton-monte-carlo-(hmc).html"],"author":"","coverImageURL":"","fullURL":"bayesian-regression.html","pathToRoot":".","attachments":[],"createdTime":1755093541175,"modifiedTime":1755099564791,"sourceSize":3903,"sourcePath":"1-Random Notes/Bayesian Regression.md","exportPath":"bayesian-regression.html","showInTree":true,"treeOrder":0,"backlinks":["bayesian-regression.html"],"type":"markdown"}},"fileInfo":{"bayesian-regression.html":{"createdTime":1755093541175,"modifiedTime":1755099564791,"sourceSize":3903,"sourcePath":"1-Random Notes/Bayesian Regression.md","exportPath":"bayesian-regression.html","showInTree":true,"treeOrder":0,"backlinks":["bayesian-regression.html"],"type":"markdown","data":null},"site-lib/scripts/graph-wasm.wasm":{"createdTime":1774702830386,"modifiedTime":1758030409505.1914,"sourceSize":23655,"sourcePath":"","exportPath":"site-lib/scripts/graph-wasm.wasm","showInTree":false,"treeOrder":0,"backlinks":[],"type":"other","data":null},"site-lib/fonts/70cc7ff27245e82ad414.ttf":{"createdTime":1774703604385,"modifiedTime":1774703604385,"sourceSize":192740,"sourcePath":"","exportPath":"site-lib/fonts/70cc7ff27245e82ad414.ttf","showInTree":false,"treeOrder":0,"backlinks":[],"type":"font","data":null},"site-lib/fonts/454577c22304619db035.ttf":{"createdTime":1774703604386,"modifiedTime":1774703604386,"sourceSize":161376,"sourcePath":"","exportPath":"site-lib/fonts/454577c22304619db035.ttf","showInTree":false,"treeOrder":0,"backlinks":[],"type":"font","data"